 to a question on the knowledge of God and the means of spiritual realisation.  The author responds by describing three degrees of knowledge, maʿrifat al-dhāt, maʿrifat al-ṣifāt and maʿrifat al-afʿāl (knowledge of the essence, of the attributes and of the actions). There then follow a series of questions and answers, and the author declares at the end of the work that all his responses are faithful reproductions of the teachings of former masters, only the arrangement and the form vary – which suggests that this is possibly not by IA as there is no-one quoted as such in the text.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>OY notes five surviving mss., the earliest of which seems to be Karacelebizade 345, which is unattributed. Later copies  are attributed to IA, but Veliyuddin 1820 does not contain a copy of the text as OY claims. More work is needed as the texts have not been correlated. </DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL></ROW><ROW MODID="88" RECORDID="3"><COL><DATA>64</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>3</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>K. Awrād al-usbūʿ</DATA></COL><COL><DATA> كتاب الأوراد الأسبوعية</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Probable IA.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Awrad</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>bismillāh fātiḥi l-wujūd</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>A collection of fourteen prayers, one for each night and day of the week. For a detailed structure and analysis of the prayers, see Pablo Beneito and Stephen Hirtenstein Seven Days of the Heart (Oxford, 2000), with critical edition as Prayers for the Week (Oxford, 2021).</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>There are no historic mss. and all the surviving texts are late, though always attributed to IA. The earliest dated copy is Carullah 1094 (939H), but Veliyuddin 1833 may be older. According to Stephen Hirtenstein and Pablo Beneito it is authentic on textual grounds, and the lack of early copies is attributed to the work being only copied for close disciples, not open diffusion.There is another relatively early manuscript of Evradü’l-Eyyami’s-Seb’a (dated 949H or 950H)  in Topkapi E.H. 1072 with 42 folios according to the online catalogue at https://topkapisarayi.gov.tr/en/manuscripts</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Ch 416 &amp; 440</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL></ROW><ROW MODID="94" RECORDID="4"><COL><DATA>68</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>4</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>K. al-Azal</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>كتاب الأزل</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Verified A.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Azal</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>IA</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>al-ḥamdu lillāh al-dāʾim alladhī lam yuzal </DATA></COL><COL><DATA>On the meaning of the term azal (eternity) in the predecessors of IA such as al-Hallāj and al-Sulamī. The alternative title (K. al-thamānīn wa thalāthīn = 38) refers to the abjad total of the word azal.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Verified by at least five historic mss. The holograph Yusuf Aga 4868 was written in 615H in Malatya, and Carullah 2111 is copied from an original which was read before IA. According to OY, it was written 601H in Jerusalem on the basis of  a note on Veliyuddin 51, but our investigation shows that no place or date is given. (See Jane Clark and Denis McAuley Some Notes on the Manuscript Veliyyudin 51, JMIAS 40, 2006.)</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>86</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>92</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>I, 692</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL></ROW><ROW MODID="98" RECORDID="5"><COL><DATA>70</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>5</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>K. al-ʿAẓama </DATA></COL><COL><DATA>كتاب العظمة</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Verified A.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Azamah</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>IA</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>602</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Holograph copy, with samāʿ 617H in Aleppo (Veliyuddin 1759)</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Konya<