riginal in the hand of the author, possibly YA 4868? According to OY, the work was written in 602H in Jerusalem on the basis of  a note on Veliyuddin 51, but our investigation shows that no place or date is given. (See Jane Clark and Denis McAuley Some Notes on the Manuscript Veliyyudin 51, JMIAS 40, 2006.)</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>79</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL></ROW><ROW MODID="70" RECORDID="7"><COL><DATA>91</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>7</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Bulghat al-ghawwāṣ</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>بلغة الغواص</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Not IA.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Bulghat al-ghawwas</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Ḥusayn al-Ḥusaynī (d.718)</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>al-ḥamdu lillāh wa-salām ʿalā ibādihi alladhī iṣṭafā wa-ṣalawātuhu ʿalā sayyidinā Muḥammad wa-ālihi wa-ṣaḥbihi. Subḥānuka Allāhumma wa-biḥamdika tabāraka ismuka</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>OY: Treatise on esoteric knowledge, its nature, its scope, its limits. Also, on prophethood, the imamate and the Seal of the saints. The poetry is mainly drawn from Ghazālī’s Sirr al-ʿālamīn, with some pieces by IA and by authors quoted in his Muḥāḍarat al-abrār. See Julian Cook’s notes on University 3184 in the on-line catalogue for more information about the poems.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>No historic mss. and only late post-900H copies, many of which are unattributed. According to Michel Chodkiewicz, who has examined the text, this is not by IA but likely to be by someone influenced by IA’s doctrine and using his technical vocabulary, possibly writing in the Ottoman era. JC finds this with one of the variants of the title (Nuzhat al-arwāḥ) attributed to Ḥusayn b. ʿAlim al-Ḥusaynī (d. 718/1318), in Izmir Milli vol.2 3019 (ms 401) and other mss. Other attributions in TRF include: Ömer b. Süleymân Halvetî [Nuzhetu’l-ervâh] and Şemseddin Muhammed b. Mahmud eş-Şehrezuri, 687/1288 [work: Nüzhetü’l-ervah ve ravzatü’l-efrah.] Earliest dated copy seems to be Ragib Pasa 823 ff.1-288 (870H), but there may be a copy in Escurial 417 dated 799H.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL></ROW><ROW MODID="31" RECORDID="8"><COL><DATA>98</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>8</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Daʿwat al-asmāʾ al-ḥusnā</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>دعوة الأسماء الحسنى</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Unverified.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Dawat al-asma</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>A collection of liturgical prayers.  To each Name there is a particular corresponding prayer.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>No historic mss. and the only surviving ones are late, without attribution to IA.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL></ROW><ROW MODID="64" RECORDID="9"><COL><DATA>103</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>102</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>9</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Dīwān ishrāq al-bahāʾ</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>ديوان إشراق البهاء</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Extract.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Diwan ishraq</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>A collection of IA poems in abjad order, ending in lām-alif, personally made by ʿṢalāḥ al-dīn ʿAbd al-Ḥusayn, plus some additional verses which have not yet been identified. Julian Cook’s analysis shows it to be derived from RG 102, from a version of what he calls the ‘Western Dīwān’ .(See Cook/Hirtenstein: The Great  Diwān  and its offspring; the collection and dispersion of Ibn ʿArabī’s poetry, in JMIAS 52, 2012 for a discussion of the different versions of the Dīwān.)</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Two mss. mentioned by OY, the earlier being the Berlin copy (1079H). However, there is another copy in the Bodleian Library (Pococke 275), which predates the others (980H).</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL></ROW><ROW MODID="115" RECORDID="10"><COL><DATA>125</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>10</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>K. al-Fanāʾ fī al-mushāhada</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>كتاب الفناء في المشاهدة</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Verified A.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Fana fi mushahada</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>IA</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>?</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Baghdad</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>al-ḥamdu lillāh alladhī qaddara wa-qaḍā wa-hakam</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>An extended meditation upon Surat al-Bayyina (Q 98) describing the experience of mystical vision and the difference between people of real knowledge and people of intellect. </DATA></COL><COL><DATA>OY lists 33 mss., of which four can be considered historic, although none  is definitive. The note on NO 2406 cannot be regarded as completely reliable, and the text in Shehit Ali 1375  is dated at 722H only on the basis of other works in the collection. But the work appears in other very good collections, such as Carullah 986 and Beyazit 3750, and has been very widely copied. It is also mentioned in the FM, and there is internal evidence of authenticity in the text.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>II, 632. Chapter 286.  </DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL></ROW><ROW MODID="180" RECORDID="11"><COL><DATA>135</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>11</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>al-Futūḥāt al-Makkiyya</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>الفتوحات المكية</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Extract</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Futuhat</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>IA</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>629/636</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Damascus</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>al-ḥamdu lilāh alladhī awjad al-ashiyāʾ ʿan ʿadam wa-ʿadamahu wa-awqaf wajūdahā ʿalā tuwajjah kalimihi li-nataḥaqqaq bidhālik sir ḥudūthhā wa-qidamahā min qidamahi</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Ibn ʿArabī’s great summary of esoteric knowledge, consisting of 560 chapters and extending to nearly 10,000 pages in the holograph. It totalises all aspects of his work and all the esoteric knowledge of his era. The first recension, completed in Ṣafar 629H, exists only in copies, while the second, written between 632H and 636H, survives in IA’s own hand (see Evkaf Muzesi 1845+).There is still work to be done in distinguishing between the two recensions in the mss base, but considerable progress has been made by Julian Cook and Claude Addas in identifying “markers” which indicate the recension of any given ms. Their research indicates that many later mss. may be hybrids of the two recensions. For details of their work on the two recensions, see ancillary documents. </DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Verified by many mss. in both recensions. The best of the second recension is Evkaf Muzesi 1845+ in 37 volumes, which is the original in IA’s hand, written in 636H and carrying  over 71 samāʿ. </DATA></COL><COL><DATA>50</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>50</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL></ROW><ROW MODID="145" RECORDID="13"><COL><DATA>150</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>13</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Fuṣūṣ al-ḥikam</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>فصوص الحكم</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Verified A.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Fusus</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>IA</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>627H</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Damascus</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>al-ḥamdu lillāh munzil al-ḥikam ʿalā qulūb al-kilam</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>The most famous and widely read of all Ibn ʿArabī’s works, containing the epitome of  his teachings on the meaning of the perfect human being (al-insān al-kāmil). It takes the form of 27 chapters on the prophets from Adam to Muhammad, each associated with a knowledge; for example; the wisdom on divinity in the word of Adam: the wisdom of light in the word of Joseph. Ibn ʿArabī’s intention in the Fuṣūṣ  is to draw out the interior, saintly wisdom of each prophet rather than the religious law which they brought.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>A much copied and commented on work, verified by at least seven historic mss. The best is Evkaf Muzesi 1933, which is SQ’s riwāya. written in his hand in 630H, with two samāʿ  in IA’s hand. Other early mss: Kastamonu Hk 2024 (710H), Paris 1340 (726H), Corum Hk 3909 (728H), Konya Ak 308 (757H) </DATA></COL><COL><DATA>187</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>194</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL></ROW><ROW MODID="70" RECORDID="15"><COL><DATA>205</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>15</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>K. al-Hū</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>كتاب الهو</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Verified A.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Hu</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>IA</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>al-ḥamdu lillāh wa-kafā wa-salām ʿalā ʿibādihi alladhīna aṣṭafā, rawī ʿan al-nabī…</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>The symbolism of the personal pronoun ‘He’ (huwā), represented, in the order of the alphabet, by the last letter, yāʾ.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>OY cites 26 mss., of which three are historic. The best are Veliyuddin 51, 762H(c), copied from an original in the hand of IA, and Yusuf Ağa 7838 which is undated, but from SQ’s library so presumed before 673H. According to OY, it was written 601H in Jerusalem on the basis of  a note on Veliyuddin 51, but our investigation shows that he has confused the place of copying with the place of writing and in fact, no place or date is given. (See Jane Clark and Denis McAuley Some Notes on the Manuscript Veliyyudin 51, JMIAS 40, 2006.)</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>75</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>80</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL></ROW><ROW MODID="43" RECORDID="16"><COL><DATA>219</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>16</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>K. al-Ḥaqq</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>كتاب الحق</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Verified A.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Haqq</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>IA</DA