sts of 14 contemplations in the style of Niffarī’s Mawāqif. There are two commentaries, one by Ibn Sawdakīn and one by Sitt al-ʿAjam, which have been used in a critical Spanish edition and an English translation of Mashāhid. There are two associated works; a prologue which is classifed by OY as RG 626, and a commentary by Ibn Sawdakīn classified as RG 684.  </DATA></COL><COL><DATA>A much copied work, verified by three historic mss. The best is probably Manisa 1183 (651H, copied by a direct disciple of IA’s) and Veliyuddin 1782 (929H, copied from an original dated 596H). Some texts include the prologue (RG 626) and an epilogue. We have classified all these under RG 432 as it is too complex to make distinctions. Michel Chodkiewicz has examined both the Manisa ms, and the Paris National ms (B. N. 6104). He finds a slight difference between them in Ibn ʿArabi’s commentary.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>37</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>38</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL></ROW><ROW MODID="75" RECORDID="51"><COL><DATA>462</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>51</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>K. al-Mīm</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>كتاب الميم</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Verified A.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Mim</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>IA</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>617H</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Aleppo</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>al-ḥamdu lillāh fātiḥ al-ghuyūb wa-shāriḥ al-ṣudūr </DATA></COL><COL><DATA>On the symbolism of the letters mīm, wāw and nūn, and all the letters which make up these names. </DATA></COL><COL><DATA>OY lists 24 mss., of which six can be considered historic. The best are Veliyuddin 1759, which is a holograph with a samāʿ  dated  617H in Aleppo, and Shehit Ali 2813 (621H, copied by Ayyūd b. Badr). </DATA></COL><COL><DATA>69</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>74</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL></ROW><ROW MODID="66" RECORDID="52"><COL><DATA>475</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>52</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Mirʾāt al-ʿārifīn</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>مرآة العارفين</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Not IA.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Mirat al-arifin</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Muhammad al-Shīrīn?</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>al-ḥamdu lillāh alladhī akhraja min al-nūn mā adraja fī al-qalam wa-abraza al-wujūd bil-jūd mā aknaza fī al-ʿadam...</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>An esoteric interpretation of the Fātiḥa. At the beginning of the treatise the author mentions IA as the Seal of Muhammadian sainthood, and quotes passages from K. al-Tajalliyāt and FM.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>OY lists 15 mss., none of which can be considered historic. OY doubts whether this is  work of IA, as does Michel Chodkiewicz, as the only mss. that attribute it to IA are very late. The earliest copies (Husein Celebi 448 (997) and Manisa 1191 (957)) attribute it to Shaykh Nāṣir al-Dīn. Another attribution (Aysofia 4248) is to Muhammad al-Shīrīn, who was a student of SQ’s (see Ragib Pasha 1453). William Chittick (see Sophia Perennis, vol. IV, 1, 1978, p.49) thinks that it is by SQ, whilst Sayyid Hasan Askani, who published an English translation (Reflections of the Awakened, London, 1983), hesitates between SQ and Imām Ḥusayn (or Mirza Husayn). The most likely conclusion is that this is not by IA, but by an early disciple of either IA or SQ. (See Julian Cook’s comments on the web-site catalogue http://archive.ibnarabisociety.org/wordpress_mias_archive/index.php/uncategorized/ragib-pasha-1453-280b-286a-3_1357-2/#comments)</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL></ROW><ROW MODID="60" RECORDID="53"><COL><DATA>484</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>53</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>K. al-Muʿashsharāt</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>كتاب المعشرات</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Verified A.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Muashsharat al-maymuna</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>IA</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA