fī muḥāḍarat al-abrār</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Using the same format as Sulamī’s book Maqāmāt al-awliyāʾ, a book of adab, with many stories from al-Andalus and people that IA knew.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>A much copied work, of which there are no historic mss, although Ahmad III A2415 is dated 712H.  Brocklemann, according to OY, thinks it is apocryphal and should be attributed to Dhahabī (d.748) (see OY p. 397). But there is textual evidence that it is by IA: Claude Addas, in her biography of IA Quest for the Red Sulphur (Cambridge, 1993), refers to several passages where incidents are described which correspond to information in other verified texts; eg. pp. 211,  223, 227. Also, a work of this title is mentioned in both the lists which IA made of his own works, Fihris muʾallafāt al-shaykh al-akbar (RG142) and Ijāza li-l-malik al-Muẓaffar (RG 269). Michel Chodkiewicz relates that some years ago he saw an autograph copy, written in Malatya, which is in private ownership in Tunisia, but we have not yet been able to obtain a copy of this. Other mss identified:  Ragib Pasha 1204 (944H); Veliyuddin 2573 ff. 1-275 (945H); Düğümlü Baba 392 (950H)</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>174</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>186</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL></ROW><ROW MODID="56" RECORDID="58"><COL><DATA>511</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>58</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>K. al-Muqniʿ fī īḍāḥ al-sahl al-mumtaniʿ</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>كتاب المقنع في إيضاح السهل الممتنع</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Verified A.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Muqni</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>602H</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Damascus in Jumādā l-ūlā 602H (Vel.51/115a)</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Damascus</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>mimman nasāmā (nasāmī) fa-sammā, wa-kharaja ʿan kulli arḍin wa-samā</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>An alchemical treatise on the esoteric knowledge symbolised by living water. </DATA></COL><COL><DATA>OY lists 16 mss., of which three can be considered historic. The best is Yusuf Ağa 7838 (undated, but most probably written in IA’s lifetime). According to OY, the work was written in 601H in Jerusalem on the basis of notes on Veliyuddin 51 and Bayazid 3750. But our investigation of Vel. 51 shows that he has confused the place of copying with the place of writing and in fact, the note says it was written in Damascus in 602H. Bayazid 3750 likewise does not mention Jerusalem, but confirms the date  of Jumādā l-ūlā 602H. (See Jane Clark and Denis McAuley Some Notes on the Manuscript Veliyyudin 51, JMIAS 40, 2006.)</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>58</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>61</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL></ROW><ROW MODID="65" RECORDID="59"><COL><DATA>530</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>59</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>R. al-Khirqa</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>رسالة الخرقة</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Verified A.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Khirqa</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>IA</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>633</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Damascus</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>al-ḥamdu lillāh alladhī khalaʿa ʿalā ʿibādihi ahli al-ʿināyatihi asmāʾahu al-husnā </DATA></COL><COL><DATA>A late work, it gives a detailed list of  ‘investitures’ through which the Shaykh received initiation into the Path, including one by the hidden guide, al-Khiḍr.  </DATA></COL><COL><DATA>OY lists 19 mss., of which one can be considered historic: Esad Ef. 1507 (999H, copied from an original dated 633H in IA’s handwriting and corrected by him). Many mss. are incomplete. Veliyuddin 51 contains only the 599H khirqa,  but it is also copied from an original in the hand of IA. Further mss: Bankipore ms 955/2 (778H?)</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL></ROW><ROW MODID="71" RECORDID="60"><COL><DATA>532</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>60</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>K. al-Naṣāʾiḥ</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>كتاب النصائح</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Verified A.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Nasaih</DA