s and by direct inspiration. The middle section,  describing his early education with over 70 teachers in Spain and North Africa, was translated by R W J Austin in the 1970s and published as Sufis of Andalusia  (London, 1971); it has subsequently become one of the best known texts by IA in modern times.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>A much copied work, verified by three historic mss. The best is undoubtedly University A79 which is in the hand of SQ’s father and is the riwāya (transmission) of al-Ḥabashī, dated 600H, with at least nine samāʿs in IA’s lifetime.  </DATA></COL><COL><DATA>52</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL></ROW><ROW MODID="53" RECORDID="66"><COL><DATA>665</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>66</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>al-Shajara al-nuʿmāniyya</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>الشجرة النعمانية</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Not IA.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Shajarat numaniyya</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>ʿAbd al-Raḥmān al-Bastamī?</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>al-ḥamdu lillāh alladhī bayana al-tabayyun li-ahl al-ʿirfān</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Concerns the future Ottoman empire and its conquest of Egypt. Although it was one of the best-known works by IA during Ottoman times, and it is still attributed to him in many modern printed editions, contemporary scholarship is unanimous in considering it apocryphal.  </DATA></COL><COL><DATA>OY lists five mss. and numerous copies of commentaries attributed to SQ and al-Ṣafadī. However, none of the mss are historic and there are strong textual grounds for considering the work to be apocryphal. The best analysis has been done by Denis Gril’s in JMIAS 43, 2008; Varia Turcica, 33, Paris, Montréal, 1999.  </DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL></ROW><ROW MODID="100" RECORDID="67"><COL><DATA>716</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>67</DATA></COL><COL><