tion came in 604H in the meeting with Qurrat al-ʿAyn.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>A much copied work, both on its own and with the commentary (RG116). There are no definitive historic mss. to verify the text in its own right, but there are several for the commentary, which includes the text of the poems. The best copies are therefore contained within mss. of Dhakhāʾir . The best stand-alone mss. are Manisa 6596 (undated, taken from SQ’s copy), and Ragib Pasha 1453 (although very late, probably also taken from SQ’s copy). There is an issue with the preface on this work. There are two basic variants; some mss carry the same preface as the commentary, Dhakhāʾir al-alāq (RG 116. Others have a longer version which begin with a khutba and IA’s account of meeting the young girl, Niẓam, who inspired the poems in Mecca. The situation is complex, with several other variants appearing in some mss (see Jane Clark Mystical Perception and Beauty: Ibn ʿArabī’s Preface to Tarjumān al-Ashwāq in JMIAS 55, 2013). </DATA></COL><COL><DATA>176</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL></ROW><ROW MODID="52" RECORDID="81"><COL><DATA>834</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>81</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>K. al-Yaqīn</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>كتاب اليقين</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Verified A.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Yaqin</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>IA</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>602H</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Hebron</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>al-ḥamdu lillāh alladhī arā Ibrāhīm malakūt al-samāʾ wa-l-arḍ </DATA></COL><COL><DATA>On the intuitive knowledge which leads to certitude. Written in Palestine in the Mosque of Yaqīn (see Veliyuddin 1826). Shehit Ali 1341 also has a note about its composition in 602H, stating that it was written in one day on Wednesday 14th Shawwāl 602H on the way to visit the tombs of Lot and Abraham.       </DATA></COL><COL><DATA>OY lists 27 mss., of which at least two can be considered historic. The best is Veliyuddin 1826 (c.825H, copied from an original by Ayyūb b. Badr and read before IA in 621H). </DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>2:205. and 2:204-206. </DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL></ROW><ROW MODID="129" RECORDID="88"><COL><DATA>30</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>88</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>K. ʿAnqāʾ mughrib</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>كتاب عنقاء مغرب</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Verified A.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Anqa</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>IA</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>595</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Almeria</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>ḥamidtu ilāhī wa-l-maqāmu ʿaẓīmu</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Written after a vision in 595H, this work is devoted to bringing out the role of the mahdī – the “rightly guided leader” – and the Seal of the Saints (whom he identifies with Jesus), discussing both a prophetic aspect which looks to the unfolding of their functions in time, and a mystical aspect which understands them as realities which can be realised in the heart of the complete human being.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Verified by at least four historic mss. The best is Berlin Oct. 3266 (described by Gerald Elmore  in  Islamic Sainthood in the Fullness of Time (Leiden, 1999) pp. 197-199), which was written in 597H, and is the oldest known  ms. of  IA’s. Also excellent is Private 1, written  in 637H by a well-known disciple, Muḥammad b. ʿAbd al-Qādir al-Anṣāri, in Damascus and checked against the original in IA’s hand; however, according to Abrar Ahmed Shahi, who has prepared a critical edition of the text, this mss contains only about 50% of the work.Another early copy, dated 707H in the Turkish catalogue (http://ktp.isam.org.tr/), is Veliyuddin 1743 ff.1-79. Another copy, dated 834H, in Milli Hk 15 ff.12b-43b, is available in digital reproduction here: https://www.yazmalar.gov.tr/detay_goster.php?k=77129JC notes that most of the poems from ʿAnqāʾ mughrib are also found as a block – and as complete poems – in the Dīwān, p. 26-33. </DATA></