ins with hājis), with an introduction, which was written in Malatya in 615H (see Milli 571, 668H), and version C which was included in the FM (II 128–34; Chapter 173, the response to al-Tirmidhī’s question 153), and consists of version B in reverse order with added questions linking each term.  </DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL></ROW><ROW MODID="31" RECORDID="117"><COL><DATA>745</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>117</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Tahdhīb al-akhlāq</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>تهذيب الأخلاق</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Not IA.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Tahdhib akhlaq</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Yahyā b. Adī (d.974)</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>591</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>A treatise aimed at students of alchemy, telling them to be wary in their desire for the transmutation of metals, which leads to neglect the One, Necessary Being who is God. Title seems to be confused with R. al-akhlāq written in 591H by IA (FM 4:59).</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>OY lists four mss. The real author is Yahyā b. Adī : see two articles by K. Samir, Arabica, vol. XXI, 2, June 1974, pp. 111-139 and vol. XXVI, 2, June 1979, pp. 158-178. (Michel Chodkiewicz)</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>201</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>72</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL></ROW><ROW MODID="143" RECORDID="118"><COL><DATA>13</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>118</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>R. al-Aḥadiyya</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>رسالة الأحدية</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Not IA.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Ahadiya</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Awḥad al-Dīn Balyānī (d.686)</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Treatise on the meanings of Unity of Being and self-knowledge. </DATA></COL><COL><DATA>OY lists 14 mss. although none can be considered historic mss. The earliest dated copy we have found 