, both of which are late: Esad Ef. 1777 (1004H), and Berlin 2956 (post-966H, poss. 1026?). Esad Ef 1777 contains several other works not found elsewhere, one of which is also found in Berlin 2956. K. al-Ghayāt is written by a good source, ʿAbd al-Karīm b. M. al-Sāliḥī al-ʿUraybī, who served at IA’s tomb in Damascus. It is not impossible that he had access to copies which are not known elsewhere. Nevertheless, this must be considered as not yet authenticated from the mss. base.  OY’s classification of this work under RG 380 is spurious, as that is a different verified text. </DATA></COL><COL><DATA>164</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>174</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL></ROW><ROW MODID="70" RECORDID="266"><COL><DATA>28</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>266</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>K. al-Amr al-muḥkam</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>كتاب الأمر المحكم</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Verified A.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Amr muhkam</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>IA</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>602</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>In Damascus in Jumada al-ūla 602H (see Vel.51/110b)</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Damascus</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>al-ḥamdu lillāh alladhī hadānā li-hadhā wa-mā kunā li-nahtadī lawlā an hadānā Allāh lamma qāl Allāh taʿalā li-nabihi...</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>The title translates as “The Firm Rule regarding the conditions necessary for people on God’s Path”. The aim of the work is to give advice to spiritual guides on the kind of language and teaching which should be offered to different types of students. </DATA></COL><COL><DATA>A much copied work, verified by at least six historic mss, three of them definitely copied from originals. The best are  Shehit Ali 1341, written around  724H in Damascus, copied from an original by IA and certified by him, and Ayasofya 4875 (probably dated 705H). OY believed the work was written in Konya in 602H on basis of a note in Veliyuddin 51 (110b), but further inspection of the note shows that the place of writing is Damascus. (See Jane