erfect Man in The Tāʾiyya of Ibn ʿArabī (unpublished, MIAS Symposium, Oxford 1998). All copies we have seen are attributed to IA (varying in length  but at least 400 verses). A line-by-line commentary by Abdullah Bosnevi entitled Qurrat ʿayn al-shuhūd also testifies to its authorship by IA. In light of the importance given by Bosnevi to this poem, it is most likely that the original Tāʾiyya should be considered as an authentic work.Critical edition by Yusuf ‘Awda (Cairo, 2015)</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL></ROW><ROW MODID="26" RECORDID="314"><COL><DATA>761</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>433</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>314</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>al-Tanazzulāt al-layliyya fī al-aḥkām al-ilāhiyya</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>التنزلات الليلية في الأحكام الإلهية</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>OY duplicate.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Layliyya</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>IA</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>According to the printed edition, a series of masāʾil with answers</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>According to Michel Chodkiewicz, this is the same as RG 433 and should be classified under that RG number.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL></ROW><ROW MODID="45" RECORDID="315"><COL><DATA>46</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>nc</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>315</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>R. fī Asrār al-ḥaḍra al-ilāhiyya</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>رسالة في أسرار الحضرة الإلهية</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Not IA.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>asrar</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>ʿAbd al-Razzāq Kāshānī (d.730)</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>A treatise on the reality of the divine Essence (dhāt).</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>According to OY and GE, this treatise is properly attributed to al-Kashānī (d.730/1329).</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><