l-ḥamdu lillāh alladhī hadānā li-hadhā wa-mā kunā li-nahtadī lawlā an hadānā Allāh laqad jaʿat rusul rabbina bi-l-ḥaqq</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Wise sayings, accompanied by explanatory notes. IA says in the introduction that it is a collection of sayings by a certain mystic called ʿAlī al-Kurdī who was ‘smitten with divine love’, and he has appended a commentary on these sayings.  Claude Addas adds: “Al-Ajwiba al-‘Arabiyya fî sharh al-nasâ’ih al-Yûsufiyya est une commentaire par Ibn ‘Arabî d’une risâla concernant les devoirs du murîd à l’égard de son shaykh rédigée par  Yûsuf b. Ibrâhîm al-Shâfi’î sous l’inspiration de la rûhâniya de ‘Alî al-Kurdî, un “fou” (muwallah ) notoire de Damas (I.A. l’a rencontré, cf.,Fut., II, 522, ed. Bûlaq).”</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>OY lists five mss. of  which two, Husein Celebi 447 and Yusuf Aga 4860, although undated, are very early, whilst  Yusuf Aga 4860 is from SQ’s library, and is possibly 7th or 8th century. The internal evidence of the text – for example, the language and the mention of his wife – is strong evidence that it is by IA. In addition, the title is listed in one of the lists which IA made of his own works, Fihris muʾallafāt al-shaykh al-akbar (RG142), and it does not seem to be attributed to anyone else.  Claude Addas confirms this stating that:: “L’attribution de ce texte  à Ibn ‘Arabî ne fait aucun doute ; on y trouve de nombreuses références autobiographiques, par ex, l’investiture de la khirqa par ‘Abd Allâh b. Jâmī”.A number of the poems in this work appear clustered in the Paris Diwan (B.N. 2348) and seemingly nowhere else. Further information on the fully digitized text of RG 9 found in Word format at cb.rayaheen.net/userfiles/download.php?id=1395‎, which extracts as a Word document with name شرح روحانية الشيخ الكردي.doc. The text itself carries a title not listed by Osman Yahia under RG 9, namely: شرح ما نطقت به روحانية سيدي علي الكردي .JC has compared that text to Yusuf Aga 4860 and Husein Celebi 447. The 202 page text in the Word document closely matches the complete text found in Husein Celebi 447 ff.1a-149b. Decapitated Yusuf Aga 4860 p.207 – which we estimate is missing the first 14 pages (7 folios) – starts with the text found at the end of page 11 of the Word document (cf. Husein Celebi f.9a line 2).PDF versions are also available via Google (شرح روحانية الشيخ الكردي لسيدي ابن عربي.pdf).</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>191</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL></ROW><ROW MODID="44" RECORDID="340"><COL><DATA>56</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>135</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>340</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Asrār al-Qurʾān</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>أسرار القرآن</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Extract.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Asrar</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Commentary upon the Fatiḥa, extracted from Chapter 5 of FM (1:110-117).  </DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Only one ms. in Carullah 2111, and although OY claims that all the texts in this collection were taken from originals, this one does not have a note saying so.  We have found another copy in Carullah 1034, but it is clear that this was copied from 2111. This  text is actually from Chapter 5 of FM (1:110-117), although the poems are drawn from ch. 5, 6, 7 and 12.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>1/110-117</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL></ROW><ROW MODID="22" RECORDID="341"><COL><DATA>77</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>341</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Baḥr al-shukr fī nahr al-fikr</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>بحر الشكر في نهر الفكر</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Not IA.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Saʿd al-Dīn Ḥamawayh (d.649)</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Treatise composed in 635H in Damascus, according to author at end of text. Probably by Saʿd al-Dīn Hamawayh. [sh09]</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Only two ms. – Hudayi 423 and Musée d’Irak 597 – listed by OY. These collections, which seem to be identical, have traditionally been attributed to IA, but Michel Chodkiewicz has established that probably all the works are by Saʿd al-Dīn Ḥamawayh, who was a contemporary of IA living in Damascus at the same time.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL></ROW><ROW MODID="39" RECORDID="343"><COL><DATA>209</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>135</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>343</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Ḥaḍrat al-ḥaḍarāt</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>حضرة الحضرات</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Extract.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Hadra</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>IA</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>An extract from Chapter 558 of FM (4:318-444).</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>OY lists two mss., one of which (Carullah 986) he identified as being copied from an original. We have not been able to verify this provenance, and the work has in any case been identified now as an extract from FM. However, JC notes that Carullah 986 is probably a first recension text, and the text appears to be in two reordered blocks: 60a-62b is end of ch. 558, and 63a-78b is beginning, suggesting the text copied from was out of order?</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>4, pp. 318-444</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL></ROW><ROW MODID="24" RECORDID="344"><COL><DATA>256</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>344</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Khātimat risālat al-radd ʿalā al-yahūd</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>خاتمة رسالة الرد علي اليهود</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Not IA.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Saʿd al-Dīn Ḥamawayh (d.649)</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Work composed in 635H in Damascus.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Only one ms. – Musé