commentary.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>OY lists five mss., of which we have investigated four. The work is verified by three historic works: Shehit Ali 1174 (741H,  copied from an original riwāya Ibn Sawdakīn), Veliyuddin 1673 (677H) and Yusuf Ağa 7838 (640H from SQ’s library). There is also a work of the same title attributed to ʿAbd Allah Bosnevi (d. 1054/1644) which has caused some confusion.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL></ROW><ROW MODID="46" RECORDID="354"><COL><DATA>689</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>354</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>K. Shawāhid al-ḥaqq fī al-qalb</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>كتاب شواهد الحق في القلب</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Verified A.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>shawahid</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>621</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Damascus</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>hādhā kitāb yataḍamman mā taʾtī bihi shawāhid al-ḥaqq fī al-qalb...</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Maxims, consisting of a number of short conundrums, counsels, instruction, intimations, quotations and allusions. Gerald Elmore (see ‘A Selection of texts on the theme of praise from some gnomic works by Ibn ʿArabī’ in JMIAS 23, pp. 58-85) feels that this text is closely related to K, al-Tarājim (RG 737), which is probably the ‘mother’ text, but further research is needed to ascertain which came first.  </DATA></COL><COL><DATA>OY lists 24 mss., of which six can be considered historic. The best is Yusuf Ağa 4868, which is an autograph, but the ms. has been stolen and we only have a digitised microfilm copy. The next best is Shehit Ali 2813 (621H, written by Ayyūb b. Badr in Damascus and read back to the author). </DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>53</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Autograph ms/semāʿ</DATA></COL></ROW><ROW MODID="61" RECORDID="355"><COL><DATA>169</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>355</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>K. al-Jalāla</DATA></COL><CO