tes of the earlier mss. Further work needed.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>I, 51-91</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL></ROW><ROW MODID="30" RECORDID="375"><COL><DATA>149</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>433</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>375</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Fuṣūl min kitāb al-masāʾil</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>فصول من كتاب المسائل</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Extract.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Fusul  masail</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>A section of RG 433, K. al-Masāʾil.  </DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Only one ms. listed for this work, Shehit Ali 1341, which has been identified as being extracts from K. al-Masāʾil.  </DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL></ROW><ROW MODID="47" RECORDID="376"><COL><DATA>384</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>376</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Madkhal fī ʿilm al-ḥurūf</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>مدخل في علم الحروف</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Probable IA.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Madkhal</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>al-ḥamdu lillāh al-mulhim asrāruhu wa-muṭliʿ shumūs ʿilmihi...</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Treatise on the science of letters, a relatively simple work of letter correspondences.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>OY lists four mss: he considers it a resumé of  RG 297, ʿIqd al-manẓūm , and the mss. are classified in a very confusing way between the two RGs. A quick check of all the mss. shows that they are fundamentally the same work, with some variations. We therefore suggest reclassifying all of them under RG 384. There are no definitive historic mss., although Shehit Ali 1341 is early. OY has Veliyudin 51 as copied from an original, but in our opinion the note refers to the previous work (See Jane Clark and Denis McAuley in JMIAS 36). Nevertheless, the work appears in many early collections and there is a good case for its authenticity.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL></ROW><ROW MODID="38" RECORDID="377"><COL><DATA>402</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>377</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>R. al-Maʿlūm min ʿaqāʾid ʿulamāʾ al-rusūm</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>رسالة المعلوم من عقائد علماء الرسوم</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Verified A.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>malum</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>IA</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>602</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Damascus on 3 Jumādā 602H (Vel.51/114a)</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Damascus</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>ajtamaʿa arbaʿat nafar min al-ʿulamā fī qubbat Arīn</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Treatise on four kinds of knowers (ʿulamāʾ) at the Well of Arīn (axis mundi): those of the west (maghrib), those of the east (mashriq), those of the north (shimāl) and those of the south (yamīn), and their kinds of knowledge. See also FM 1:38-41.  </DATA></COL><COL><DATA>OY cites seven mss. Verified by one historic ms.,Veliyuddin 51 (762H, copied from an original composed in Damascus in 602H). Milli 2988 is the same text, but the other two mss. we have consulted are different texts. Confused with RG 34 and others. Further work needed.Further mss identified by JC: Tunis, Dar al-Kutub al-Wataniya 641, and Escurial ms 417 / 4 (f. 117-131?)</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>62</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>66</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>1, 38-41</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL></ROW><ROW MODID="33" RECORDID="378"><COL><DATA>411</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>135</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>378</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Manzil al-ʿārif al-Jibrāʾīlī</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>منزل العارف الجبرائلي</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Extract.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Manzil ghibrili</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Chapter 303 of FM.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>There is only one ms listed by OY, Carullah 2111, which 