l”, which is extant in Chester  3490 seems to be a copy of it by IA. See also RG 633, which seems to also be the same work. </DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL></ROW><ROW MODID="36" RECORDID="393"><COL><DATA>803</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>393</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>K. al-ʿUrūsh</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>كتاب العروش</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Not IA.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Urush</DATA></COL><COL><DATA> Abū al-Fatḥ M. al-Wafāʾ (?)</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>On two types of knowledge; human and Divine. The former is the product of reason, the latter a projection in the heart. (OY). </DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Only three mss. copies according to OY and none of them early or historic. Both Haci Mahmud 2313 and Esad Ef. 1631 are copied from the same text dated 747H by the author, but there is no indication  that this was in IA’s hand. A work of this title is listed in both the lists which IA made of his own works, Fihris muʾallafāt al-shaykh al-akbar (RG142) and Ijāza li-l-malik al-Muẓaffar (RG 269),  but it is not necessarily this text. The work is also attributed to Abū al-Fatḥ M. al-Wafāʾ (probably the correct author). </DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>257</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL></ROW><ROW MODID="53" RECORDID="394"><COL><DATA>821</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>394</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Waṣiyya fī kayfiyyat ḥuṣūl al-maʿrifa al-quṣwā</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>وصية في كيفية حصول المعرفة القصوى</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Probable IA.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Wasiyya</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>alladhī awṣika bihi ayyuhā al-akh</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>According to OY, deals with intuitive knowledge and how this can be obtained.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>OY lis