Y 692/3). However there  are textual reasons to question the attribution, as  it states that the author spent a year in prison, which there is no record of IA having done so. According to OY, it is also attributed to Jamāl al-Dīn Yūsuf al-Ṣafadī (possibly son of Aḥmad al-Ṣafadī, d.742/1341)) in Fatih 5375. However, some scholars, particularly Bakri Aladdin, believe it is by IA, so for the time being it is classified as unverified. Julian Cook notes that RG 332 (Kashf al-asrār wa hatk al-astār (another work sometimes attributed to IA)), is attributed to Jamāl al-Dīn Yūsuf b. Hilāl al-Ṣafadī (d. 684/1285). If he is the same author, then those dates would mean he could not be a son of Aḥmad al-Ṣafadī, d.742/1341.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL></ROW><ROW MODID="36" RECORDID="537"><COL><DATA>675</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>338</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>537</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Sharḥ al-asmāʾ al-ḥusnā wa-taḥqīqātihā bi-l-basmala al-sharīfa wa-l-fātiḥa li-l-Shaykh al-Akbar</DATA></COL><COL><DATA> شرح الاسماء الحسنى وتحقيقاتها بالبسملة الشريفة والفاتحة للشيخ الإكبر</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Unverified.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Sharh asma</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>qāla Allāh tabāraka wa-taʿālā wa‑lillahi l‑asmāʾu l‑ḥusnā fa‑idʿūhu bihā fīhi dalīl...</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Treatise on the Seven Essential Attributes and the Divine Names. Halet 245 gives explanation of the seven  Attributes (only Life, Power, Will, Hearing, Seeing mentioned) and the Names under the rubric of muqaddima fī taḥqīq dāʾirat al-raḥmān. It appears to be 99 Names in order specified by Ghazālī. </DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Only two copies of this work, neither of them historic (see OY p.461). OY also classifies Halet 245 under Kashf al-Maʿnā (RG338), but our inspection reveals that it is definitely not. It seems to use akbarian terminology and schema, so worthy of further investigation.  </DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL></ROW><ROW MODID="27" RECORDID="538"><COL><DATA>51</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>538</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>K. al-Asrār al-thalātha</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>كتاب أسرار الثلاثة</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Unverified.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Asrar</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Unveiling of the secrets of esoteric knowledge (OY). </DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Only one ms., Esad Ef. 1777/76a-82b. This is late, and in a collection where there are several other works with only one or two supporting manuscripts. The scribe is a known source, who copied at least 20 works  attributed to IA (see Esad Ef. 1507, Carullah 2120, Kutahya 911 and Orhan 606); he served at IA’s tomb in Damascus (see Esad Ef. 1777/192a). However, the attribution of this work to IA must be regarded as unproven.  </DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL></ROW><ROW MODID="30" RECORDID="539"><COL><DATA>221</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>539</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Ḥaqq al-waqt</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>حق الوقت</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Not IA.</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Haqq</DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Saʿd al-Dīn Ḥamawayh (d.649)</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA>Only one mss given by OY: Shehit Ali 1351/162b-163b. Although this is an early ms., dated 690H, and attributed to IA, the same work is attributed to Saʿd al-Dīn al-Ḥamawayh on other mss. (see Husein Celebi 442).  </DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL></ROW><ROW MODID="18" RECORDID="540"><COL><DATA>366</DATA></COL><COL><DATA></DATA></COL><COL